frameDefinitions: A Complainer communicates their negative emotional reaction to some state of affairs in a Complaint to an Addressee.
A Communicator communicates a judgment of an Evaluee to an Addressee.
This frame contains words for types of noise which can be used to characterize verbal communication.
A Whole separates into Parts, or one part of a whole, called Part_1, becomes separate from the remaining portion, Part_2.
In this frame, a Communicator judges the Addressee and then communicates that appraisal directly to the Addressee.

A Speaker talks about a Topic, which may be an action performed by the Speaker or an entity or state of affairs that they are associated with in order to suggest that the Speaker is worthy of admiration.
frameExamples: The top US commander in Iraq <t>complained</t> to the Pentagon last winter that his supply situation was so poor that it threatened Army troops' ability to fight.
I <t>commended</t> his handling of the crisis.
'Don't treat me as a child!' she <t>cried</t> scornfully.
This small channel meanders through marsh and wetland, <t>splitting</t> into several smaller channels that empty into Lake St. Clair.
The principal <t>rebuked</t> the student for cheating on the exam.
Turkish officials <t>boasted</t> of giving 'tens of thousands of dollars in surreptitious payments' to a prominent American politician.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Complainer</fen> is the sentient entity that produces the <fen>Complaint</fen> (whether spoken or written).
The lamentable situation that the <fen>Complainer</fen> is communicating to the <fen>Addressee</fen>.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the subject matter to which the <fen>Complaint</fen> pertains.
<fen>Medium</fen> is the physical entity or channel used by the <fen>Complainer</fen> to transmit the <fen>Complaint</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the complaint is made.
This role specifies the location where the complaining takes place.
The <fen>Communicator</fen> uses language in the written or spoken modality to convey his or her evaluation of the <fen>Evaluee</fen> to another person.
<fen>Medium</fen> identifies the physical or abstract setting in which the evaluation is conveyed.
<fen>Topic</fen> identifies the entity to which the proposition or propositions conveyed relate.
A judgment is made about the <fen>Evaluee</fen>  With verbs this role is typically expressed as Object:
<fen>Expressor</fen> is the body part or action by a body part that conveys the judgment made by the <fen>Communicator</fen>.
Typically, there is a constituent expressing the <t>Reason</t> for the <fen>Communicator</fen>'s judgment. It is usually a <ment>for</ment>-PP.
When the communication of the judgment takes place.
Where the communication of the judgment takes place.
<fen>Speaker</fen> is the sentient entity that delivers the <fen>Message</fen>.
Message has a number of different realizations in this frame, including <ment>that</ment>-clauses, direct quotes, infinitival complements, <ment>for-to</ment> phrases, and NP Objects.
<fen>Topic</fen> occurs in PP Complements, usually headed by <ment>about</ment>.
The <fen>Voice</fen> describes the <fex name=''>Speaker'</fex>s utterance or other message-encoded production.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> where the Communication noise event occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where an event occurs.
The <fen>Whole</fen> is a single entity or an aggregate of entities which separates into <fen>Parts</fen>.
This refers collectively to the Parts resulting from separation of a Whole:
Part-1 is the first of two Parts mentioned.
Part_2 is the second of two Parts mentioned. This is usually a PP Complement.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the separation occurs.
Where the separation occurs.
The <fen>Communicator</fen> communicates a judgment to the <fen>Addressee</fen>.
The <fen>Addressee</fen> is jduged by the <fen>Communicator</fen> and receives the message of approval or disapproval.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the subject on which the <fen>Addressee</fen> is being judged.
The <fen>Reason</fen> is why the Communicator forms the type of judgment they form.
The <fen>Medium</fen> identifies the physical or abstract entity in which the judgment is conveyed.
An action or entity under the control of the <fen>Communicator</fen> that expresses the criticism or praise directed towards the <fen>Addressee</fen>.
The point in time at which the <fen>Communicator</fen> berates or compliments the <fen>Addressee</fen>.
The location where the <fen>Communicator</fen> admonishes the <fen>Addressee</fen>.
The <fen>Speaker</fen> is the person who produces a message about a <fen>Topic</fen>.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is a positively judged entity or state of affairs with which the <fen>Speaker</fen> is associated and about which they talk.
<fen>Medium</fen> is the physical entity or channel used by the <fen>Speaker</fen> to transmit the statement.
A description of the state of affairs that redounds to the <fen>Speaker</fen>'s credit
<fen>Expressor</fen> is the body part or action that conveys the feeling of pride of the <fen>Speaker</fen>.
The time when the statement is made.
The role specifies the place where the statement takes place.
